        [],
        [
          "You had no idea when you visited that monstery archive in the Transylvanian mountains hunting down a prosopographical reference to the lineage of Vlad Tepes that the legends would turn out to be true.  Your sire told you when she met you that she was a local antiquarian doing genealogical research on her family.  She was so glamorous, so elegant - such a change from the dour and colorless people back in Bucharest at the university where the newly-installed communist government seemed to have squeezed all of the life out of the place.    She invited you back to her family's villa and you didn't even think to wonder how they had kept ahold of it under the Communists.  You found out soon enough.   LIfe under Ioana's thumb was awful.   Once the blood bond had its hooks into you she became imperious, cruel, and disdainful.   Your nights became an endless slog of pointless errands, stifling shows of antiquated etiquette (in which any missteps were punished horribly) and occasional orgies of horrifying violence and blood.  You found yourself longing for your graduate student days back in Bucharest.   So when Ulyanenko and the others found you that fateful night when you were down in the village collecitng a baby, it was like a godsend.   You've since devoted yourself to the pack's well-being - a good deal of that sense of courtliness and hospitality has rubbed off on you from Ioana, and you're grateful for that for all that you delighted in watching her burn.    But you are still somehwhat troubled - and rankly repulsed - by much of what you've seen of others of your blood.  The discipline of Vicissitude sickens you and its exercise roils your long-dead stomach.  Fortunately, there are none in your pack who practice it.    And you do your best to grit your teeth when you encounger others of the Sabbat who do"
        ],
